  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- The International Money Laundering Abatement and Anti-Terrorism Financing Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Money Laundering Crime)\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (Monetary Transaction in Criminally Derived Property)\n\n3. State Statutes:\nMany states also have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n\n4. Key Elements Typically Addressed:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained money\n- Conducting financial transactions with proceeds from criminal activities\n- Reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Penalties including fines and imprisonment\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds and make it harder to profit from criminal activities by creating legal mechanisms to track and prosecute financial crimes.\n\nEnforcement is typically handled by agencies like the FBI, IRS Criminal Investigation Division, and Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN).",
